
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `cut` baraye joda kardan ghesmat-haee az khtoot dar file-ha ya voroodi estandard be kar miravad. Shoma mitoonid ba estefade az in dastoor, столун-ha (columns) ya field-haee ra ke ba delimiter-ha joda shode-and, joda konid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `cut -d'delimiter' -ffield_number`  --> ✂️ Joda kardan field ba delimiter moshakhas va shomare field.
    🔹 `cut -ccharacters` --> 🔤 Joda kardan character-ha az har khat.
    🔹 `cut -bbytes` --> 💾 Joda kardan byte-ha az har khat.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ cut -d':' -f1 /etc/passwd

    🔹 Joda kardan username az file `/etc/passwd` ke ba `:` joda shode ast.

    $ cut -c1-5 file.txt

    🔹 Joda kardan panj character aval az har khat dar file `file.txt`.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ echo "ali,reza,hossein" | cut -d',' -f2

    🔹 Ba delimiter `,`, field dovom (reza) joda mishavad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `cut` command is used to extract sections from each line of files or standard input. You can use it to extract columns or fields that are separated by delimiters.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `cut -d'delimiter' -ffield_number` --> ✂️ Extract a field using a specified delimiter and field number.
    🔹 `cut -ccharacters` --> 🔤 Extract characters from each line.
    🔹 `cut -bbytes` --> 💾 Extract bytes from each line.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ cut -d':' -f1 /etc/passwd

    🔹 Extract the username from the `/etc/passwd` file, which is separated by `:`.

    $ cut -c1-5 file.txt

    🔹 Extract the first five characters from each line in the `file.txt` file.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ echo "ali,reza,hossein" | cut -d',' -f2

    🔹 With the delimiter `,`, the second field (reza) is extracted.

